722056f.text:
Park Ave., west side, north from and including East 35th., to, but not including East 36th Streets. Also shown is East 35th Street, north side, west from Park, to Madison AvOs. The Church of the Covenant is on Park Ave., at the N.i. corner of East 35th Street. On the same block but at the N.E. corner of Madison Ave., is the Protestant Episcopal Church of the Incarnation.
Prior to 1890.
Eugene L. Armbruster, Collection.

722051f.text: Park Avenue, at the N. W. corner of 35th Street, showing the Church of the Covenant. This church, built for the Liberal Presbyterian denomination, was dedicated in 1865, and stood here until demolition(about 1891. The site was then occupied by three small residences, Nos. 26, 28, and 32 Park Avenue. The corner house No. 20, will later be occupied by the Women's City Club and in 1939 will be replaced with a modern apartment house. Note the fence around the center parks; it is probably the original fence of the 1860s and will remain as it is till 1923. To the left, on Madison Avenue appears the steeple-less Church of the Incarnation.

722049f-b.text:
Park Avenue, south from East 35th Street, showing prominently the towered 71st Regiment Armory at the S. E. corner of 34th Street. Note at the right the construction details of the Fred F. French constructed apartment house, No. 16 Park Aenue. Adjoinfng same is the Community Church at 34th Street. View 2 is thru the church clearance, where the apartment house, No. 10 Park Awenue is being erected. The utilitarian structure in the background is the well known No. 1 Park A enue uilding. See newspaper files for litigation between this corporation and Mrs. Bacon who sought to retain thts Rddress for her Swiss Chalet residence at the N. W. corner of 34th Street. A view of the lattar is obstructed
by the lamppost tn the earlier photo.
View 1: January 1924
Nugene L. Armbruster
View 2: April 15, 1931
P. L. Sperr

712234f-a.text:
35th Street, north side, east from and including Park Avenue, showing 28 Park Avenue, the Advertising Club, on the N.E. corner.  The church is the Church of the Epiphany (Protestant Episcopal) at the N.E. corner of Lexington Avenue.
February 19, 1929.

722050f-a.text: Park Avenue, facing north from 38th Street, showing the Grand Central Station (pre-Metlife Building).

722052f-a.text:
(1)
Park Ave., east side, north from 35th Street, showing the old Robb mansion, occupied since 1922 by the Advertising Club, on the N.E. corner of 35th Street. At the S.E. corner of 37th Street may be noted the 9-story apartment built in 1923 on the site of the old Judge Russell house, and behind it, on the horizon, the towering Chanin Building recently erected at Lexington Ave. and 42nd Street. In the left background may be seen the Grand Central Station and the New
York Central Building (1928) beyond it.
March 27, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, exclusive of the N.E. corner of East 35th Street.
Pebruary 19, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.
According to the New Lork Times of October 18, 1937, No. 29 Park Ave. (third building from right in No. 2) has been purchased by the Association for the Improvement of the Poor (A.I.C.P.) and will be utilined as a dental climic to replace the present clinic on the N.E. corner of Lexington Ave. and East 22nd Street,which will be demolished for an addition to the Childrens Court. No. 29, was erected in 1908 by Mrs. A. Murray Young, as a copy of a London
Residence.

722060f-b.text:
Park Avenue, west side, from 35th Street, to a point between
36th and 37th Streets.
On the N. W. corner of 35th Street, where the old Church of the Covenant stood from 1865 to 1895, is shown the house occupied by the Women's City Club. Behind it towers the new building at 10 East 40th Street.
March 10, 1929
P. L. Sperr
(2)
A portion of the former view at a slightly later date. Note the vacant lot at No. 30. This site was utilized for a wing
to the adjoining structure.
The dominant No. 10 East 40th Street Building (erected 1928) partly obscures the newer No. 500-Fifth Avenue Building. To the right appears the southerly side of the recently constructed Union League Club. This building is at the S. W. corner of Park Avenue and East 37th Street and was erected in 1930.
February 23, 1931
P. L. Sperr
(3)
Details of the demolition of the Women's Club and its isomorphic structure, No. 28 Park Avenue, the property of F. F. Guthrie. Upon this site will rise a tall apartment building. The five-story affair at the left will not be included. This bears No. 39 East 35th Street and is occupied by the United Lutheran Church of America.
October, 1938
George D. Chinn

730416f-a.title: General view - [Manhattan - Park Avenue - 35th Street (Northwest).]
730416f-a.text:
A general view, northwest from 17 Park Ave., south from 35th Street, showing the Chanin Building (at the left) and the Chrysler Building
(at the right) in the background.
February 27, 1931.
P. L. Sperr.

722053f-a.text:
Fark Avenue, east side, at 35th Street, showing the two apartment houses on the S.E. corner built from 1923 to 1926, and the old Ro65 mansion on the N.E. corner, which has housed the Advertising
Club since late 1922.
In the foreground may be seen the excavation left by the Community Church at the N.w. corner of 34th Street, and on the horizon the new Daily News Suilding on 42nd Street east of Third Avenue.
April 15, 1931.
P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

722057f-a.text:
Fark Avenue, west side, from 35th to 37th Streets, showing part of the Women's City Club on the N.W. corner of 35th Street and a vacant lot at 30 Park Avenue left by demolition of an old 5-story
house.
On the S.W. corner of 37th Street is shown the new clubhouse of the
Union League Club, shortly after completion.
February 27, 1931.
P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

Park Avenue, at the N. W. corner of East 35th Street, showing the Church of the Covnant. At the left is an extensive view westward to Madison Avenue. At the N. E. corner there is the Church of the Incarnation. Note the absence of the spire atop same. This feature was added
